# How Did Canada Get Involved in World War II?  
## An In-Depth Report

---

## Introduction

Canada’s involvement in World War II (WWII) marked a pivotal moment in its history, reflecting its evolution from a British dominion to a sovereign nation with independent foreign policy. Unlike in World War I, when Canada was automatically at war following Britain’s declaration, Canada exercised its legislative independence and made a conscious decision to enter WWII. This report explores the circumstances, motivations, and processes that led Canada to join the war, emphasizing its sovereign status, political deliberations, military preparedness, and contributions. The analysis is based on a comprehensive review of historical sources and expert accounts.

---

## Historical Context and Sovereignty

### Statute of Westminster 1931: Legal Independence

Canada’s ability to declare war independently was established by the Statute of Westminster in 1931. This statute granted full legislative independence to Canada and other British dominions, allowing Canada to make sovereign decisions regarding foreign policy, including declarations of war ([Rossignol, 1992](https://www.canada.ca/en/department-national-defence/services/military-history/history-heritage/official-military-history-lineages/lineages/war-of-1812/war-of-1812-canadian-declaration-war.html)).

Unlike in 1914, when Canada was automatically at war with Germany following Britain’s declaration, in 1939 Canada was not legally bound to join the conflict. This independence was demonstrated when Canada waited a week after Britain declared war on Germany before making its own declaration.

---

## The Decision to Enter the War

### Timeline of Declaration

- **September 1, 1939:** Nazi Germany invades Poland.
- **September 3, 1939:** Britain and France declare war on Germany.
- **September 7, 1939:** Canadian Parliament reconvenes early to debate war.
- **September 9, 1939:** Parliament votes almost unanimously to declare war.
- **September 10, 1939:** Canada officially declares war on Germany.

Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King requested King George VI’s approval to declare war, symbolizing Canada’s sovereignty by having the King act as the Canadian monarch, not the British monarch ([Fortin, 2008](https://www.canada.ca/en/department-national-defence/services/military-history/history-heritage/official-military-history-lineages/lineages/war-of-1812/war-of-1812-canadian-declaration-war.html)).

### Political and Social Factors

The decision was influenced by several factors:

- **Close Ties to Britain:** Canada had strong cultural, familial, and economic connections to the United Kingdom. Many Canadians, especially English Canadians, felt a moral obligation to support Britain ([Holterman, 2019](https://www.quora.com/Why-did-Canada-join-World-War-II-Was-it-forced-to-because-it-was-on-the-leash-of-the-United-Kingdom)).

- **Emerging National Identity:** The week-long delay before declaring war was a deliberate act to assert Canadian autonomy, contrasting with the automatic entry in WWI ([Granatstein, 2009](https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/letters/letters-to-the-editor/article-parliament-will-decide/)).

- **Threat Perception:** After the fall of France in 1940 and the Battle of Britain, Canada recognized the strategic threat posed by Nazi Germany to the British Commonwealth and global security ([Cantor, n.d.](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9LZl3r1G8qQ)).

- **Domestic Political Considerations:** Mackenzie King balanced English Canadian support for the war with French Canadian opposition, particularly regarding conscription, leading to cautious policies initially focused on volunteer enlistment ([Legion Magazine, 2019](https://legionmagazine.com/en/2019/09/should-canada-have-gone-to-war-in-september-1939/)).

