## Military Preparedness at War’s Outset

At the start of WWII, Canada was militarily unprepared:

| Branch               | Strength (1939)                              | Equipment Status                 |
|----------------------|---------------------------------------------|--------------------------------|
| Army                 | 4,500 regulars + 51,000 reservists          | Virtually no modern equipment  |
| Royal Canadian Navy   | 15 ships, 1,800 officers                      | Small fleet, limited combat potential |
| Royal Canadian Air Force (RCAF) | 4,061 personnel, only 235 pilots | 275 aircraft, only 19 modern   |

Despite this, Canada rapidly mobilized, expanding its forces exponentially during the war ([Canada and World War II, Britannica](https://www.britannica.com/event/World-War-II/Canada-in-World-War-II)).

---

## Canada’s War Contributions and Role

### Military Engagements

- **Battle of Britain:** Canadian airmen fought alongside the Royal Air Force, contributing significantly to the defense of Britain ([Cantor, n.d.](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9LZl3r1G8qQ)).

- **Dieppe Raid (1942):** A costly but important learning experience for Canadian troops that informed later amphibious operations ([WW2DB, 2007](https://ww2db.com/country/canada)).

- **Italian Campaign and Normandy Invasion (1944):** Canadian forces played key roles in the liberation of Europe, including the capture of Juno Beach during D-Day ([WW2DB, 2007](https://ww2db.com/country/canada)).

- **Liberation of the Netherlands:** Canadian troops were instrumental in liberating Dutch territories from Nazi occupation ([WW2DB, 2007](https://ww2db.com/country/canada)).

### Industrial and Economic Contributions

Canada’s industrial output surged during the war:

| Contribution                  | Quantity / Impact                         |
|-------------------------------|------------------------------------------|
| Trucks produced               | Over 800,000                             |
| Aircraft produced            | Over 16,000                             |
| Naval ships built            | 471 ships by 1945                       |
| Merchant ships built         | Over 400                               |
| Aluminum production          | 40% of Allies’ total                    |
| Nickel production            | 95% of Allies’ total                    |
| Wheat and food production    | Dramatically increased                  |

Canada became known as the "aerodrome of democracy" for its aircrew training and aircraft production ([WW2DB, 2007](https://ww2db.com/country/canada)).

### Human Resources

- Over 1,000,000 Canadians served in the military during the war, approximately one in eleven of the population.
- Around 45,000 Canadians died, and 54,400 were wounded.
- Women served in various roles, including administration, communication, and as aircrew ([Britannica](https://www.britannica.com/event/World-War-II/Canada-in-World-War-II)).

